    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-09-19T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-09-19T16:00:00-05:00" n="448"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d448">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/5207: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Irkutsk</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HEL1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harris</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">temporarily at Omsk</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-09-19T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 19, 1919, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your 383, September 12, noon.<note n="56" xml:id="d448fn56">Transmitted in
                        undated telegram from the Chargé in China, received Sept. 15, 12:30 p.m.,
                            <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> Rifles and ammunition are being shipped to <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1"
                        >Kolchak</persName> representatives, also clothing and so forth to
                    Cooperatives and railway materials to <persName corresp="#p_SJF1"
                        >Stevens</persName>. Note to Japan written only because action of Japanese
                    commanders have been making effective shipments westwards quite impossible and
                    thus making failure of this Government to assist <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1"
                        >Kolchak</persName> absolutely certain, if persisted in by Japan.</p>
                <p>Only statement of Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">Morris</persName> noted
                    by Department is press report from Vladivostok crediting him with urging all
                    help to <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName>. Department believes
                    contrary report must be ascribed to hostile propaganda. In this connection this
                    Government must point out regrettable attitude of <persName>Kalmikoff</persName>
                    and <persName>Semenoff</persName> which, regardless of question whether such
                    attitude may properly be <pb facs="0537" n="425" xml:id="pg_425"/> ascribed in
                    part to Japanese, is nevertheless apparently beyond control of Omsk authorities.
                    You may assure Soukine, that this Government appreciates the situation which
                    confronts <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName> and within the limits
                    of its legal powers to do so hopes to continue its assistance. Negotiations for
                    sale of clothing hampered by existing legislation but have nevertheless been
                    re-opened with Russian Embassy here. General Hermonius representing Russian
                    Conference at Paris has just arrived to take part in such negotiations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
